{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"82a41854-4d13-4ebc-8711-ff9bc5933055","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe report confirms the bottleneck is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation—not compilation itself. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps an in-process MSBuild server warm.\n\n## Recommendations (most to least impactful)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\nThis keeps the build host alive and only triggers incremental rebuilds on file changes—no cold-start penalty:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Ensure MSBuild Server is enabled (.NET 8+)\nThe MSBuild server keeps worker nodes alive between CLI invocations. Verify it's not disabled:\n```bash\n# Should NOT be set to 1\necho $DOTNET_CLI_DO_NOT_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER\n```\n\n### 3. Add a `Directory.Build.rsp` to guarantee node reuse\nCreate this file next to the `.csproj`:\n\n```\n/nodeReuse:true\n```\n\nThis ensures MSBuild nodes persist between invocations, amortizing JIT and evaluation costs.\n\n### 4. Use the terminal logger (`-tl`)\nReduces output overhead on .NET 8+:\n```bash\ndotnet build -tl\n```\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The biggest single win is switching to `dotnet watch build` for edit-build-test cycles—it eliminates process startup entirely, matching Visual Studio's behavior. For ad-hoc `dotnet build` calls, ensuring MSBuild server + node reuse are active will cut 1–2 seconds off each invocation.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7bd3b99f-0667-43c0-99d8-79a7cf3a66ca","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer report clearly states the issue: MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation is causing 2-4 second builds even when nothing has changed.\n\nThe key difference between Visual Studio and CLI builds:\n- Visual Studio uses an in-process MSBuild server (design-time builds keep MSBuild loaded)\n- CLI `dotnet build` spawns a new MSBuild process each time, paying startup + project evaluation costs\n\nThe main solutions for this are:\n\n1. **Use the MSBuild Server** (`dotnet build -nodeReuse:true` or set `MSBUILDENABLESERVERNODEREUSE=1`) — In .NET 8+, MSBuild has a server mode that keeps worker nodes alive between builds. \n\nThis is enabled by default in some scenarios but can be explicitly enabled. Other approaches like `dotnet watch` keep the build host warm for incremental rebuilds, and the `-graph` flag uses static graph evaluation which can be faster for multi-project solutions. For .NET 8+, the most impactful fix is enabling MSBuild Server Node Reuse through the environment variable or build flag. In .NET 7 the MSBuild server was opt-in, but by .NET 8 it's enabled by default unless you explicitly disable it. For this specific problem with MSBuild startup overhead, `dotnet watch build` is the most impactful solution since it keeps the build host alive and avoids process restarts entirely. I could also add a `Directory.Build.rsp` file to enforce node reuse and use the terminal logger for lighter-weight output.","outputTokens":1310,"requestId":"7405:17DD88:162CE68:18B9F34:6A051E52"},"id":"cf30506c-c311-4c9d-8bfd-3eb881c6ab2b","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:59:25.072Z","parentId":"43bb6e4d-a287-4f61-91bd-a99e75c61275"}
